of little relevance in the reading of early modern texts.The sense of Early Modern writing includes readings of both familiar and unfamiliar texts by Shakespeare, Sidney, Jonson, Hester Pulter and others, and considers topics such as ears, eyes, tongues, hands and voices, in order to ask: How should we read early modern texts? The book will therefore be of interest to all students and researchers in early modern or Renaissance studies, as well as to those thinking through the theories and histories of literature, aesthetics and rhetoric.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAestheticsxHistory. 0aEuropean literatureyRenaissance, 1450-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aRhetoric, Renaissance. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 4aShakespeare 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aaesthetics.  aearly modern writing.  ahistoricist.  ainfluential narrative.  aliterary studies.  amodernity.  apoetics.  areading.  arhetoric.  asense.1 aRobson, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613063140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130631423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130631/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles